Title: TO: Experts on Physics of Computation  
Author: Haiqing Wei and Xin Xue Dear Sir/Madam: 
Date: February 13, 1997  
Abstract: We would like to say a few words about the new concept of static quantum computation and its implications. We try to explain why our work should be widely interested as well as how recent research by other groups and our own work led to our discovery. Recently quantum computation (in our opinion, there should be an adjective "dynamic") has attracted lots of interests. Quantum computers may solve some problems exponentially faster than classical ones, one example is factorization. People have been seeking for more quantum algorithms to solve other NP problems efficiently using quantum parallelism. But up to now there is no further substantive progress. On the technological side, it is very difficult to implement a dynamic quantum computer maintaining the delicate quantum coherence while carrying out the desired quantum logic operations at the same time. By contrast, the new scheme of STATIC quantum computation we have just discovered has the built-in power to solve search problems. Actually we have proved that a universal quantum computer can solve all NP problems efficiently in the sense that it needs only polynomial number of static logic gates. Static computation is completed in no time or a short time irrelevant to the problem input size. Another remarkable merit of static quantum computer is that dissipation does it no harm but helps. Consequently a static quantum computer can be easily implemented. The new discovery is related to many fields of science and engineering, such as computer science, combinatorial mathematics, computational physics, quantum many-body theory, nanotechnology, physical chemistry, biophysics, even economics, etc. It will surely be widely interested. However, mathematicians and computer scientists may be astonished by our daunting conclusion that all NP problems can be easily solved on a universal quantum computer. Well, what has been found is not a great mathematical discovery but a totally new physical means of static computation which can accomplish nondeterministic programs thus solve search problems with ease. The concept of static computation has long been overlooked before our discovery. Historically, the first electronic computers used electronic tubes and then transistors whose operating principles are governed by classical physics laws to carry our logic functions. With the birth of integrated circuits, the size of the devices was shrunk 
